String Theory on Parallelizable PP-Waves 
 
 




Darius Sadri and  M. M. Sheikh-Jabbari 


Department of Physics, Stanford University

382 via Pueblo Mall, Stanford CA 94305-4060, USA  



Stanford Linear Accelerator Center,
Stanford  CA 94309, USA   




darius@itp.stanford.edu,jabbari@itp.stanford.edu 





 
Abstract 



The most general parallelizable pp-wave backgrounds which are non-dilatonic
solutions in the NS-NS sector of type IIA and IIB string theories are
considered.
We demonstrate that parallelizable pp-wave backgrounds are necessarily
homogeneous plane-waves, and that a large class of homogeneous plane-waves
are parallelizable, stating the necessary conditions.
Such plane-waves can be classified according to the number
of preserved supersymmetries. In type IIA, these include 
backgrounds
preserving 16, 18, 20, 22 and 24 supercharges, while in the IIB case they 
preserve
16, 20, 24 or 28 supercharges. An intriguing property of parallelizable pp-wave
backgrounds is that the bosonic part of these solutions are invariant 
under T-duality, while the number of supercharges might change under 
T-duality. Due to their
 exactness, they provide interesting backgrounds for
studying string theory. Quantization of string modes, their 
compactification and behaviour under T-duality are studied.
In addition, we consider BPS -branes, and show that 
these -branes can be classified in terms of the locations
of their world volumes with respect to 
the background -field.
 






Introduction 

More than a decade ago it was argued that  s provide us with 
solutions of supergravity which are -exact.
It has also been shown that any solution of classical general relativity 
(GR) in a special limit known as the Penrose limit, generates a plane-wave 
geometry 
. Plane-waves are a sub-class of s with planar
symmetries. The process of taking the Penrose limit consists of finding a 
light-like geodesic, expanding the metric about that geodesic and scaling 
all the coordinates corresponding to the other directions properly
. The Penrose limit 
has also been extended to supergravity solutions.
However, not much attention was focused on these solutions
until very recently, when it was realized 
that the string theory sigma model on a large class of s is solvable 
.
The recent interest has been further boosted  by the work of 
Berenstein-Maldacena-Nastase, BMN,
, where they noted that a specific  solution in the type IIB 
supergravity appears as the Penrose limit of  geometry 
and hence is a maximally supersymmetric solution of type IIB theory. Based 
on this observation they proposed a correspondence between certain 
operators of   super Yang-Mills theory and string theory 
on s. The BMN proposal has by now passed many crucial tests
(see for e.g., and references therein),
and has been extended to many other cases with various numbers of
supercharges. 

It has also been argued that all ten dimensional  
solutions of type IIA, IIB or heterotic supergravities 
are also -exact. In the physics sense,  
manifolds are 
those for which  there exists a (parallelizing) torsion which makes the 
manifold flat.(More precise definition of  would be 
presented in section 2.)  Besides flat space which is 
trivially , generically,  spaces are endowed with torsion 
and hence are usually ignored in the context of classical GR. 
However, they arise naturally in most string theories (with the exception of type I)
where the field strength of the NS-NS two-form field 
 is interpreted as torsion in the target space.

Generally, in these  supergravity solutions only the metric and 
 fields are turned on, i.e., these are non-dilatonic solutions 
in the NS-NS sector of IIA or IIB supergravities.   
As we will prove in section 3, as a result of ,  the  
variation of the gravitinos vanishes for 32 independent solutions 
and hence all the restrictions on the number of supercharges
come from the dilatino variations.

In this work we will focus on s which are  and prove that in 
general the s are necessarily of the form of homogeneous  s and 
also show that a large class of homogeneous  geometries are , including  
the geometries coming as Penrose limits of  and 
. We also argue that  survives the Penrose 
limit, and hence the Penrose limits of  geometries(
Note that this geometry is not a solution of , this will 
be clarified more in section 3.2.)  are also 
s. We show that general s form a family of -exact 
supergravity solutions determined by four real parameters. Then we proceed 
with counting the number of supercharges for these s. We 
show that the maximum number of supersymmetries for a  is 28 which 
corresponds to a IIB  background with  rotational symmetry,
a solution which has appeared previously in reference. 

Performing a Michelson transformation, we study 
toroidal compactification of our solutions and their behaviour under 
T-duality. A remarkable property of s is that the bosonic part of such 
solutions are invariant under T-duality; however, due to the change in the 
boundary conditions, the number supersymmetries of such T-dual solutions 
might be different. We recall that this property is a generic feature of 
all 
homogeneous s, regardless of whether they are  or not. 
In general, we show that a  in type IIA with  
supercharges is T-dual to the same geometry in type IIB with 
 or  supersymmetries. In addition, there exist
 solutions for which . Therefore, for 
there is the possibility of finding self T-dual solutions.

In section 6, we formulate string theory on the most general  
background and show that in light-cone gauge it is solvable with a 
particularly simple spectrum. We also study T-duality at the level of 
string theory. In our case, as a result of the existence of a non-zero 
NS-NS H-field, the right and left-movers of closed string modes enter
differently. Specifically, only left (or right) movers appear in the zero-modes.
This in particular leads to the peculiar property that the 
zero-mode in one direction behaves as the momentum mode of another 
direction. Hence, the
string is probing a non-commutative cylinder where its fuzziness is 
inversely proportional 
to the -field strength, as well as the light-cone momentum. 
We then turn to the question of -branes in the  backgrounds 
and briefly discuss which classes of BPS -branes can exist in these backgrounds.
A full analysis of these -branes is postponed to future works.

The paper is organized as follows: Section 2 contains a review of
needed material. We first review the definition of s, s and 
homogeneous s and fix our conventions and notations. We then state 
the definition of  and some facts about  manifolds. In 
section 3, we present implications of  for supergravity and its 
solutions. In section 4, we prove that all  s are
homogeneous s and classify the s by the amount of supersymmetry 
they preserve. In section 5, we discuss toroidal compactification of 
s as well as their invariance  under a large class of T-dualities.
In section 6, we study superstring theory on s and work out the 
bosonic and fermionic  string spectrum (in the light-cone gauge). In 
section 7, we study T-duality on the string spectrum. In section 8,
we briefly discuss -branes on s. The last section is devoted 
to concluding remarks and open questions.



 

 



Reviews 


In this section we review, very briefly, some of the necessary facts about 
the two basic ingredients of this paper, 
s and . For more detailed discussions of these topics the reader is 
referred to the literature.



Review of pp-waves 


A general class of space-times with interesting properties are given by
pp-waves . They are defined as space-times which support a 
covariantly constant null Killing
vector field ,
 





In the most general form, they have metrics which can be written as 
 
where  is the metric on the space transverse to a pair of 
light-cone directions given by  and the coefficients
,  and  are constrained by 
(super-)gravity equations of motion.
The pp-wave metric () has a null Killing vector
given by  which is in fact 
covariantly constant by virtue of the vanishing of .
The most useful pp-waves, and the ones generally considered in the 
literature, have  and are flat in the transverse directions, i.e.
, for which the metric becomes
pp'metric 
ds^2  = 
-2 du dv -F(u,x^i) du^2 + _ij  dx^i dx^j . 
Existence of a covariantly null Killing vector field of the space-time 
implies that all the higher dimensional operators built from curvature 
invariants vanish and hence there are no -corrections to 
s of the form () which are solutions of classical 
supergravity.(
In general, if  the statement
about -exactness is not true and the transverse metric, , 
itself may receive -corrections, however, there are no extra 
corrections due to the wave part of the metric.)  
For string theory, however, the existence of this null Killing vector
leads to a definition of frequency (in light-cone gauge) which is 
conserved and as a result, the usual problem of non-flat space-times, 
namely the particle (string) creation, is not present.

A more restricted class of pp-waves, the plane-waves , are those 
admitting a globally defined  covariantly constant null Killing 
vector field. One can show that for s
 is quadratic in the  coordinates of the transverse space,
but still can depend on the coordinate ,
, so that the metric takes the form
 
Here  is symmetric and by virtue of the only non-trivial
condition coming form the equations of motion, its trace is related to
the other field strengths present.
For the case of vacuum Einstein equations, it is traceless.

There is yet a more restricted class of plane-waves, homogeneous plane 
waves, for which  is a constant, hence their metric is of the 
form
homometric 
ds^2  = 
-2 du dv -_ij  x^i x^j du^2 + dx^i dx^i  ,
with  being a constant.(
This usage of the term homogeneous is not universal. For example,
the term symmetric plane-wave has been used infor this form of the metric, reserving homogeneous for a wider subclass of plane-waves.
) 


Parallelizability 


An  dimensional manifold M is said to be parallelizable if there exists
a smooth section of the frame bundle, or equivalently, if there exist 
smooth sections of the tangent bundle T(M), such that they are linearly
independent at each point of M.  More intuitively, 
a manifold is 
parallelizable if one can cover the whole manifold with a single non-degenerate
coordinate system. 
In general, most manifolds are not
parallelizable.  However, group manifolds are always parallelizable. A
well known result of K-theory due to Adams is the
classification of all parallelizable spheres. These consist only of ,
 and . One can demonstrate the parallelizability of  and
 by noting that they are group manifolds:  is the group manifold
of , while  is the group manifold of .
However,  which can be thought of as the octonions of unit norm,  
is not a group manifold
because the octonionic algebra is non-associative and so the associativity 
property of groups is not satisfied.
This result on parallelizable 
spheres is
closely linked to the Hurwitz theorem, which gives a complete
classification of the unital composition algebras (i.e. Hurwitz algebras),
as the reals, the complex numbers, the quaternions and the octonions (or 
Cayley numbers),


and the fact that ,  and  are topologically equivalent to 
the complex numbers, 
quaternions and octonions of unit norm, respectively. The 
non-parallelizability of  is
enshrined in the famous no hair theorem.
We should also note that, for the reason stated above,  the 
Lorentzian version of , i.e.,  
is also .  

There is another definition of parallelizable manifolds due to 
Cartan-Schouten:
A manifold is called parallelizable if there exists a torsion which 
"flattens" the manifold, i.e. makes the Riemann curvature tensor vanish.
We caution the reader that the definitions of  we have given 
here, which is the one assumed in the physics literature, is known in the 
mathematics literature as absolute parallelism, and is a stronger condition than 
the mathematical definition.
In general, absolute parallelism implies parallelism, but not vice-versa.

Let us make explicit the decomposition of the 
connection into a  piece and a torsion contribution:
 ^ _ =  ^ _ + 
T^ _   ,
where  is symmetric in  indices and  
 (torsion) is anti-symmetric. The curvature 
 may be decomposed in a similar way, into a piece
which comes only from the  connection and the torsional 
contributions:
curvature 
