(_)^2 -1 12  H^2) .
Since we are interested in solutions involving only the metric and 
torsion, we set the dilaton field  to a constant. Then the  
equations of motion for the metric and  field are
 
 
If we define  as torsion ,
as we discussed in previous section, the  equations for the metric 
and  fields are nothing but the Ricci- condition. 
Hence all  manifolds (which are obviously also Ricci-) 
satisfying the constant dilaton constraint
Dilaton 
R=1 12  H^2
are solutions of .

For any  solution one may wonder about   and  
exactness as well as (classical) stability. The  solutions which we 
are interested in are non-dilatonic and hence they are  independent. 
The -exacctness of these  solutions were studied long 
ago in reference. Computing the second  contributions 
to the string theory -functions, it was shown that such 
contributions are zero for  manifolds.(Of course, as 
in any field theory with more than one coupling, the two loop 
renormalizations are scheme dependent, and according to reference 
 in a specific scheme such contributions are zero for 
 manifolds. For further details the reader is referred to that 
reference.)  Therefore the  solutions of  are exact up to 
order . It has been argued that this property is expected to 
remain to all orders in .
    
 




