standard or kinematical Killing spinors which exist on any ,
so are always present after a Penrose-Gueven limit.
The kinematical supercharges are thus in the kernel of .
Their presence is a direct consequence of the existence of
a null Killing vector on the  space-time manifold.

Write  as diag(A,B,A,B),
with A and B themselves diagonal matrices with eigenvalues that are doubly degenerate
(up to a sign).
Now require . This amounts to the equation .
The entries of  are a set of four independent algebraic functions of
the  from which the field strength is constructed foura ,
given by , in equation constants .
Some of these  may vanish identically for a given background, and the components
of  acted on by these can be taken to be arbitrary. They provide additional
Killing spinors beyond the standard kinematical ones.
The components of  which are not projected out by the action of A in a given
background must then vanish if  is to provide a solution of the Killing
spinor equation, and so do not contribute any additional supercharges.(
Notice that it is not possible, if all  are non-zero,
to simultaneously have some  and
another . If we had not subtracted off

the kernel of  (the kinematical supercharges ),
then  alone would yield
two simultaneous equations,  and , but
since  was assumed arbitrary,  and so , which is
possible only for all , contradicting the earlier assumption.
This is another way to see that the presence
of  is central to the existence of any Killing spinors on non-trivial
s.) 
A similar argument carries through for the case of right handed spinors, where
the constraint becomes , and the four algebraic functions of interest
are now .













As an example, take the most symmetric non-trivial  background,
with , possessing
a U(4) symmetry (whose  center acts by interchanging the four planes).
Let us assume that we have subtracted off the kinematical supercharges.
For a left-handed spinor, the equations whose solutions gives rise to non-kinematical
supercharges, are ,
with the 's given in constants .
Of these, three are identically satisfied and one is not. As
a result,  of  are unconstrained.
For a right-handed spinor, the equations would be ,
and of these, none
are identically satisfied, so all of  must vanish for the dilatino variation to be
zero.
To each of these we may add 8 unconstrained supercharges which are projected out by the
action of .
This leads to the following counting of supercharges:
For type IIA, we have the standard 16, together with 6 from the left handed 
parameter and zero from the right handed one, for a total of 22 supercharges.
In type IIB, if both spinors are left handed, we have the maximal of 28 supercharges
for a non-trivial  background, while if
both are right handed, we only have 16, which is the minimum.
Clearly, for type IIA, the number of supercharges must be one of
,
while for type IIB the allowed number of supercharges is .
The sensitivity to chirality appears since the
non-zero components of right/left handed spinors appearing in
