computations are very similar to those which appear in, we do 
not present them here.

Finally, we would like to note that it is possible to have a combination of 
the three cases discussed above. For example, in the the background ,
with 28 supersymmetries, we might have a D5-brane along 
the  directions, a mixture of all three cases.  



Discussion 


In this paper we classified and studied, to some extent, the s.
We first briefly studied 
implications of  for a general  solution and proved that the 
vanishing of the gravitino variation for  backgrounds can be solved with 32
independent solution. One should note that the converse is not true,
that is, not all the cases for which the gravitino variation has 32 
solutions are parallelizable, for example, the famous  
background.
 



 
Strings on  have been studied in detail using the SL(2,)
group manifold and the corresponding Kac-Moodi algebra. 
It would be very interesting to extend the definition of the 
WZW models and the Maldacena-Ooguri setup to the  case; although it 
is not a group manifold, it has a nice (non-associative) algebraic (octonionic)
structure.

We then turned to s and proved that all  s are 
necessarily homogeneous s and the converse is true if the  
in the  term () has doubly degenerate eigenvalues.
The s may be classified by their , where for type IIB
the maximal  is 28 and the others differ by steps of four (down to 16), 
while type IIA  
may have 24, 22, 20, 18 and 16 supercharges. 
We also discussed the invariance of the bosonic sector of s under 
T-duality and discussed how the fermions and number of supercharges may change 
under T-duality.

We studied string theory on the  backgrounds and showed that the
sigma model is simpler than for other  backgrounds.
This simplicity might help in working out the vertex operators, making it possible
to study string scattering processes and to evaluate the S-matrix elements, whose
existence for  backgrounds has been argued in.
Working out the proper vertex operators and string scattering amplitudes
is another interesting open question we postpone to future works. 

We also very briefly discussed the half BPS -branes and the 
restrictions on the possible Dirichelet or Neumann boundary conditions 
arising from  backgrounds. The classification of possible 
-branes, branes at angles, intersecting branes and most importantly,
the theory residing on branes in the  backgrounds and 
the corresponding  solutions, along the lines of,
deserve 
more detailed analysis.






